# Custom Page Interactive Sections Spec

## Scope

Formik-driven forms, Q&A, surveys, polls, and voting embedded in the existing
custom-page block builder.

## Governing architecture

- Interactive types are ordinary `PageSection` values: `form`, `qa`, `survey`,
  `poll`, and `vote`.
- Definitions and settings use the typed section source when its per-page gate is
  ready. `pages.content` remains the compatibility/read projection.
- `PAGE_NORMALIZED_INTERACTIVE_RESPONSES=1|true` selects normalized response
  authority only for pages with both matched definition parity and a matched
  `page_section_response_migrations` run. Other pages retain document authority.
- `BlockRenderer` remains the dispatch host and every interactive block renders
  through the same `SectionFrame`, shared toolbar, layout, margin/padding,
  animation, copy/cut, move, and delete behavior as other blocks.
- The existing page registry validates interactive types and config bounds.
  No migration is required.

## Persistence and concurrency

- Participant writes address an existing page ID and numeric section ID. On a
  migrated page they lock the page and normalized section, mutate
  `page_section_responses`, then rebuild that section's rollback projection in
  `pages.content` in the same transaction. Non-migrated pages retain the legacy
  locked-document mutation.
- Normal builder saves lock the same page row and preserve the current interactive
  records while applying definition and presentation changes. A stale autosave
  must not erase a response submitted concurrently.
- Copying an interactive section and duplicating a page copy the design with an
  empty records array. Record data must be removed before clipboard serialization
  and rechecked on paste; user submissions must never be cloned.
- A section holds at most 50 fields and 1,000 records. Each submission is bounded,
  validated on the server, and may include an idempotency key.
- Section IDs are unique positive integers. The server rejects client-supplied
  records on page create/update and owns every record mutation.
- Idempotency keys are scoped to the authenticated participant and section. A retry
  may return only that participant's existing authorized record.
- Normalized storage retains only a SHA-256 idempotency hash and a stable
  respondent identity key. Neither raw keys nor hashes are exposed through REST,
  page reads, result projections, logs, audit metadata, or WebSockets.
- The participant client retains one idempotency key for an unchanged logical
  submission until it receives success; changing answers starts a new key.
- Polls and votes allow one record per authenticated user. Other types use their
  configured response limit (`0` means unlimited).

## Privacy and authorization

- Page visibility is checked before participation.
- Participation currently requires an authenticated user. This provides a stable
  identity for response limits without inventing a guest identity store.
- Admins, page owners, and editors may read, moderate, and delete all records.
- Moderation and deletion call the centralized `security.PagePolicy` from the page
  service. Missing policy dependencies and permission lookup failures deny access.
- Privileged record mutations emit metadata-only page audit events containing the
  page, section, record ID, action, actor, and request metadata, never answer data.
- Other viewers receive only their own records. Published/answered Q&A records are
  additionally visible as the public Q&A feed.
- Public result payloads contain aggregates for choice, boolean, rating, scale,
  and NPS fields only. Free-text values are never placed into result summaries.
- Result visibility is `never`, `after_participation`, or `always`. Raw records
  are removed server-side from page content before it is returned; CSS is never
  used as an authorization boundary.
- Page WebSocket and cache-invalidation payloads never contain raw records,
  respondent metadata, user IDs, answers, or idempotency keys.
- Interactive mutations broadcast `{id, partial: true, interactive: true}` and
  clients refetch their authorized REST projection.

## Section behavior

| Type | Participant view | Manager view |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Form | Configured fields, validation, success state | Response table and expanded disabled values |
| Q&A | Ask question; see own pending and published/answered questions | Moderation table, answer, publish/archive, pin, delete |
| Survey | Multi-field response with one-response default | Response table and structured result summaries |
| Poll | One-choice participation and policy-gated results | Response table, totals, counts, percentages |
| Vote | Review notice, confirmed single ballot, immutable participant choice | Response table and policy-gated tally |

## UI contract

- All user-entered forms use Formik, including design and moderation forms.
- Controls use existing `Button`, glass `Select`/`FormikSelect`, `TableView`,
  design tokens, and the ultra-dense page-builder spacing model.
- Manager tabs are Preview, Responses/Moderation, Results, and Design.
- New interactive blocks persist their type defaults when inserted; rendered defaults
  may not exist only in client memory.
- Response rows expose a compact expand control. Expanded content renders the
  complete submitted field set as read-only values.
- Native checkbox/radio controls have explicit dimensions and never inherit the
  global full-width text-input styling.
- Poll/vote results always pair bars with text counts and percentages.

## Existing-page API extension

- `POST /api/pages/{pageId}/sections/{sectionId}/responses`
- `PATCH /api/pages/{pageId}/sections/{sectionId}/responses/{recordId}`
- `DELETE /api/pages/{pageId}/sections/{sectionId}/responses/{recordId}`

These routes retain their response contract across storage modes. Migrated pages
use normalized response authority; the document is a rollback projection.
Definition-type checks are repeated against the locked normalized row so a
concurrent type change cannot turn Q&A moderation into another section mutation.

## Migration and rollback

- `page-interactive-response-backfill --after-id N --limit 1..500` processes
  pages in ID order and is safe to resume or rerun.
- A matched run verifies response count plus canonical response key, respondent,
  answers, status, moderator answer, pinned state, timestamps, and idempotency
  hash parity. Operational output contains counts and mismatch codes only.
- The command replaces raw rollback-document idempotency keys with one-way
  hashes. Answers remain in the rollback projection through the Phase 7 release
  window but are always authorization-filtered before REST serialization.
- A normalized page read loads interactive records from
  `page_section_responses`, never from the rollback document. The cutover audit
  verifies response parity before recording a successful rollback drill.

## Verify

- Backend: registry validation, transactional record preservation, sanitization,
  duplicate clearing, response limits, moderation authorization, and deletion.
- Frontend: defaults, validation, copied-record clearing, Formik rendering,
  manager tables, results, dense responsive styling, lint, tests, and build.
- Commands: `env GOCACHE=/tmp/skaia-go-cache GOTMPDIR=/tmp JWT_SECRET=test-secret go test ./...`;
  from `frontend/`, `npm run lint`, focused `vitest`, and `npm run build`.

